            <div type="glosses">
                <note xml:id="MIND" resp="#DCH">&#x201C;Mind&#x201D; (MS IA, <hi rend="italic">g</hi>.1)&#x2014;This word, written sideways between the columns of the poem, 
                    does not appear to be intended as part of &#x201C;Brussels&#x201D; itself; and the hand may not be <persName corresp="#JR">Ruskin</persName>&#x02BC;s, 
                    although the formation of the terminal <hi rend="italic">d</hi> is more characteristic of his hand than of <persName corresp="#MR">Margaret Ruskin</persName>&#x02BC;s, 
                    whose handwriting can sometimes be confused her son&#x02BC;s. The word seems to form an imperative; and while no other clue remains to indicate what was to be &#x201C;minded,&#x201C; 
                    the word may be a metamark (see <ref type="note" subtype="bibliographical" target="editorial_rationale_note.php#METAMARKS">Editorial and Encoding Rationale and Methodology: Element, Attribute, and Value Usage&#x2014;Metamarks</ref>).</note>
            </div>
